<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB REF="020425_0006_0FC7415F361A1518">
<HEAD>THE WIDOW's VOW.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>A Hall in a Ca&s;tle.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> JEROME <HI>and</HI> FLORA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>I Can't go at pre&s;ent, Mr. Jerome, for I expect my Lady every moment to ring, and if I &s;hould be out of the way <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> will be angry; and as I am but new in her &s;ervice.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>She angry! Oh you don't know her yet&mdash;When you have been a day or two with her you'll find &s;he <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> angry&mdash; She is the be&s;t temper'd creature&mdash;and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> not for her aver&s;ion to us men, &s;he would not <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span">.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you con&s;ider that as a fault, Mr. Jerome?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure I do&mdash;For my part, I think &s;he had much better be too fond of us, as the re&s;t of her &s;ex are.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Mr. Jerome, what cau&s;ed her aver|&s;ion to th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">n?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll tell you Flora, if it won't make you melancholy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no, Mr. Jerome&mdash;I like a melancholy &s;tory&mdash;I like dearly to cry, when it is not on my own account.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well then&mdash;when my lady was only 15 &s;he <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> with a fine hand&s;ome young fellow, interior to her both in rank and forturne; but my good old Lord, her father, who doated upon her, was afraid
<PB N="6" REF="020425_0007_0FC74164CBE885E0">
a di&s;appointment might break her heart, and &s;o con|&s;ented to her having him; but he proved &s;o bad a hu&s;band, that my poor old ma&s;ter &s;oon died with grief.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't cry yet, there's &s;omething wor&s;e to come&mdash;My Lady, on this, took &s;uch a di&s;like to her hu&s;band, that he died of grief too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Mr. Jerome, this is very moving.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Cries.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>On this&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope there is nothing wor&s;e to come?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>On this, my Lady made a vow to &s;hut her&s;elf up from the whole &s;ex.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, that is more affecting than any of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;he immediately retired to this lonely Ca&s;tle, where, except the hou&s;e of Donna I&s;abella, next door, we have not a neighbour for miles, and even there we are &s;trangers&mdash;for my part I have never &s;o much as &s;een Donna I&s;abella, or exchanged a word with any of the &s;ervants &s;ince they came to the place&mdash;tho' indeed they have not been here above eight days.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>But how long has my Lady kept this vow of avoiding all your &s;ex?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eighteen months.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eighteen weeks! what a time!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Months.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Months! &s;he has certainly lo&s;t her &s;en&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not &s;he.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>O but I am &s;ure &s;he mu&s;t have lo&s;t &s;ome of them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you no.&mdash;But I mu&s;t leave you now Mrs. Flora, for yonder is Don Antonio, and I believe he is coming this way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thought no man was admitted into the ca&s;tle but you, Mr. Jerome?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; Don Antonio lives here&mdash;but then he is my Lady's uncle; and you know there can be no fear of her falling in love with him, as he is a relation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>But <HI>you</HI> are no relation, Mr. Jerome.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="7" REF="020425_0008_0FC7416607F65C50">
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, as you &s;ay, &s;he might fall in love with me&mdash;Stranger things have happened&mdash;and to tell you the truth, &s;he does not &s;eem po&s;itive &s;he &s;han't, for &s;he bids me keep out of her &s;ight as much as po&s;&s;i|ble, for fear I &s;hould put her in mind of that hand&s;ome villain that brought her to this retirement.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here comes the old Gentleman!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I mu&s;t go, for he'll be wanting to &s;ay &s;omething to you&mdash;he is for ever running after the maids&mdash;I am &s;orry to leave you&mdash;I am, indeed, Flora; indeed I am&mdash;Oh it would be a happy thing for me if I could bring my&s;elf to care as little for the women, as my lady does for the men.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit Jerome.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>A fine &s;weetheart, truly, I have got&mdash;and if this old fright proves another, I'll be even with him.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Antonio&mdash;She courte&s;ys.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hah!&mdash;what!&mdash;what is all this!&mdash;what have we here?&mdash;what have we here? a pretty girl&mdash;a very pretty girl indeed!&mdash;My niece's new maid, I &s;uppo&s;e&mdash;Aye, aye, I had the other &s;ent about her bu&s;ine&s;s&mdash;She mu&s;t be like her mi&s;tre&s;s for&s;ooth, and have nothing to &s;ay to a man&mdash;<HI>(going up to Flora)</HI> My dear, come this way&mdash;I think your's is a new face&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir&mdash;and I think your's is an old one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hem&mdash;hem.&mdash;Pray what is your name?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>A very good name&mdash;and I intend never to change it for a bad one.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look in my face&mdash;What do you blu&s;h for?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>For you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, no pertne&s;s&mdash;but let me bid you welcome to the ca&s;tle.&mdash;<HI>(Offers to &s;alute her.)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, indeed you &s;han't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will bid you welcome to the ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(After a &s;truggle be &s;alutes her.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word, Sir, you are very rude&mdash;How would you like I &s;hould &s;erve <HI>you</HI> &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do&mdash;Do&mdash;&s;erve me &s;o&mdash;you are very welcome.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="8" REF="020425_0009_0FC74168389E85A8"><HI>Enter</HI> JEROME.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Flora, there's a young woman at the gate, who &s;ays &s;he lives with Donna I&s;abella, and wants to &s;peak to you upon &s;ome particular <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span">&mdash;Can your Honor &s;pare her with no inconvenience to your&s;elf?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;Yes&mdash;&s;he may go&mdash; <STAGE>(<HI>Exit Flora and Jerome.</HI>)</STAGE> A young woman at the gate, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> do I want to bid <HI>her</HI> welcome to the ca&s;tle&mdash;A maid of Donna I&s;abella, our neighbour&mdash;by the bye <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> bring about an acquaintance with Donna I&s;abella and the Counte&s;s my niece, if I can, for I am told I&s;abella is a very beautiful lady&mdash;and I &s;hould like to bid by welcome to the ca&s;tle&mdash;but, notwith&s;tanding all the pains I have taken, ever &s;ince &s;he has arrived to pro|cure a fight of her, I have not been able&mdash;I would, however, force my&s;elf into the hou&s;e, but it &s;eems &s;he has a young brother, the Marquis, come down on a vi&s;it to her within the&s;e three days, and he might take upon him to re&s;ent my gallantry&mdash;and I can't &s;ay I am fond of re&s;entments, rag<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> and hatred&mdash;no, no, the <HI>&s;o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">te<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"></HI> pa<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ions po&s;&s;e&s;s me <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>A Chamber at</HI> DONNA ISABELLA's.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ISABELLA <HI>followed by the</HI> MARQUIS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>But my dear &s;i&s;ter, did not you &s;educe me to this melancholy &s;pot, on a promi&s;e that you would procure me an introduction to the rich widow, the charming Counte&s;s?&mdash;Intere&s;t fir&s;t prompted my wi&s;hes, but &s;ince I have beheld her, it is love.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Beheld her!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, beheld her&mdash;walking in her garden&mdash;&s;itting negligently in an arbour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>But how?&mdash;How contriye to &s;ee her?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>From the top of our hou&s;e, through a tele&s;cope&mdash;but, my dear &s;i&s;ter, do bring us a little nearer, or I'll purcha&s;e a &s;peaking trumpet, and make love to her through it, though my pa&s;&s;ion be heard by every &s;oul within a quarter of a mile.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><PB N="9" REF="020425_0010_0FC74169DB84E430">ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you I have great hopes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>But why not accept of her acquain|tance, and prevail on her your&s;elf to &s;ee me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you again, the letters I expect from her uncle at Madrid will have more weight than vo|lumes I could &s;ay&mdash;She dare not di&s;obey him, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>And yet I would not compel her to it&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">le&s;s &s;he con&s;ents to my acquaintance freely, without being con&s;trained by force, or deceived by &s;tratagem, I had rather have recour&s;e to the top of the hou&s;e and my tele&s;cope again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do not let your &s;crupulous honor over|come all your future pro&s;pects&mdash;Notwith&s;tanding the&s;e letters will &s;trongly recommend you, yet it will be with her own con&s;ent only &s;he will yield to the recom|mendation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>But when do you expect the letters?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Every in&s;tant&mdash;my &s;ervants are now gone to the Po&s;t-office.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll fly and &s;ee if they are returned.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do; for as &s;oon as the letters are arrived I would not have you loo&s;e a moment but away, and know your fate at once&mdash;yet if &s;he will but &s;ee you I think with &s;uch a per&s;on as your's, there can be but little to fear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>But they tell me &s;he is &s;o au&s;tere &s;ince this rigid vow&mdash;&s;o awful&mdash;&s;he will petrify me with a look.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw&mdash;away, and &s;ee if the letters are come.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will, and if they are, and I gain admittance, I'm re&s;olved I will obtain you a hu&s;band within a week, in return, my dear &s;i&s;ter, for your kindne&s;s to me.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit Marquis.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> INIS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Inis&mdash;I am impatient to hear&mdash;What &s;ucce&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Delightful, Madam&mdash;I have been introdu|ced to the young Counte&s;s&mdash;I fir&s;t communicated the
<PB N="10" REF="020425_0011_0FC7416DEC914570">
intelligence of the pretended plot forming again&s;t her to her waiting woman, who was &s;ufficiently alarmed at it, to take me to her Lady immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o, Madam, as &s;oon as I was introdu|ced I fell a crying&mdash;I thought that was the be&s;t way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>And then, before I di&s;covered what I had to &s;ay, I made her promi&s;e not to betray me, which &s;he did mo&s;t &s;olemnly, and without the lea&s;t reluctance&mdash;and now, Madam, &s;ays I, I live &s;ervant with your neighbour, Donna I&s;abella, a &s;lighty Lady, who turns every thing &s;erious and &s;acred into ridicule; and &s;he has re&s;olved to make &s;port of you for pretending an aver&s;ion to men, and for that purpo&s;e &s;he has procured recommendations for you to receive the vi&s;its of the young Marquis her brother, but in&s;tead of him, &s;he propo&s;ed to come her&s;elf, di&s;gui&s;ed as a man, prevail on yon to con&s;ent to be married to her, and then throw off the ma&s;k, and make you and your vow the je&s;t of the whole kingdom.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>That is all right&mdash;go on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>On this &s;he thanked me a thou&s;and times for the di&s;covery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>But did &s;he &s;ay &s;he would receive me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh yes&mdash;&s;he has promi&s;ed to receive you on my account, that my divulging the &s;cheme may not be detected.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>You may depend upon it&mdash;but how are you to proceed now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Send my brother to her immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your brother.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;The Counte&s;s, from what you have told her, will &s;uppo&s;e him a woman, receive him, and con&s;equently &s;uffer a thou&s;and endearing familiari|ties; till, charmed by the graces of his mind and per|&s;on, &s;he &s;hall love him without <HI>knowing</HI> it, and, when &s;he detects the impo&s;tor, be unable to part with him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>And if &s;he is like me, &s;he'll think it the happie&s;t day of her life&mdash;but have you prepared your brother how to act his part?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><PB N="11" REF="020425_0012_0FC7416F0F66B020">ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>He has nothing to <HI>act,</HI> being the very per&s;on he repre&s;ents, and therefore &s;hall not know of the art by which he is introduced&mdash;for, except being a little too attentive to dre&s;s and etiquette, a circum|&s;tance which, with his youthful appearance, favours our de&s;ign, he is one of the mo&s;t amiable young men in the world, and the lea&s;t idea of impo&s;ition would &s;hock his honour, and put an end to my &s;cheme.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then he is not to know he is to be taken for a woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly not&mdash;Hu&s;h, here he is, now for my credentials. <HI>(Taking out letters from her pocket.)</HI></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MARQUIS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my dear, &s;i&s;ter, there are no let|ters arrived.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, here they are&mdash;(<HI>Gives a packet of letters</HI>) my maid has ju&s;t brought them me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>O with what joy I receive them&mdash;they are all right?&mdash;There will be no mi&s;take I hope?&mdash;Nothing to make me appear ridiculous?&mdash;I would not appear ridiculous for the world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>All is right&mdash;No, no.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>They are addre&s;&s;ed to her uncle!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, becau&s;e it will be far more delicate to be introduced through his means&mdash;but there is one enclo&s;ed to her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>D'ye think &s;he'll &s;ee me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; I dare &s;ay&mdash;There is little doubt of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>By my dream la&s;t night, I'd lay my life &s;he will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, what did you dream?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I dreamt &s;he ordered her &s;ervants to drag your Lord&s;hip by force out of the hou&s;e, and duck you in the great fi&s;h-pond for a whole hour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is that a &s;ign?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>O yes&mdash;Dreams always go by contraries.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(Going, returns.)</HI> But I know &s;he is &s;o haughty and re&s;erved, that, <HI>&s;hould</HI> &s;he admit me, I &s;hall appear confu&s;ed and awkward.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><PB N="12" REF="020425_0013_0FC7417C86C81968">INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>So much the better&mdash;&s;he expects you'll be awkward.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Expects I &s;hall be awkward!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw, p&s;haw&mdash;He&s;itate no longer with your fears, but away&mdash;you know your fir&s;t court mu&s;t be to the uncle, and when you have been a little time in the hou&s;e your apprehen&s;ions will vani&s;h&mdash;Away, away.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>But if &s;he &s;hould not conde&s;cend to &s;ee me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>INIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my Lord, you may depend upon it &s;he will, becau&s;e of my dream.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exit Marquis on one &s;ide and I&s;abella and Inis on the other.)</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE>The Hall in the Ca&s;tle.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> FLORA <HI>and</HI> JEROME.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha, ha.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha, ha&mdash;But is all this matter of fact?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>As true as I am alive, Jerome&mdash;I have done nothing but laugh ever &s;ince I heard it&mdash;But do you think, Jerome, &s;he'll be dre&s;t all over like a man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, every thing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;every thing&mdash;Egad, I long to have a peep at her!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, and &s;o would Antonio too, if he knew.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, that he would&mdash;he'd be &s;o fond of the young Marquis there would be no keeping him away from her&mdash;but he does not know of it, you &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; no &s;oul knows of it yet but my Lady and I, and now I have told it to you; and I am to tell it to all the &s;ervants as &s;oon as &s;he comes, that they may not think my Lady has broken her vow, by ad|mitting a man&mdash;Lord, I wonder how I &s;hould look in men's clothes!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's the Prie&s;t's old great cloak, doublet, and jack-boots hanging up behind that door,
<PB N="13" REF="020425_0014_0FC7417DFA161630">
if you have a mind to try, and I'll &s;tep out of the way till you put them on.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(A loud rapping at the door.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here &s;he is&mdash;Here &s;he is&mdash;Oh dear&mdash;Oh dear&mdash;how a&s;hamed I am for her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I wi&s;h I may die if &s;o ben't I.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Covering his eyes.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>And yet &s;omehow I long to &s;ee her!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Another rapping.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Run, Jerome, run.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>This moment <HI>(turning back)</HI> but I am &s;o afraid I &s;hall laugh.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>O no&mdash;Don't laugh&mdash;if you do you will &s;poil all, and my Lady will never forgive you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well&mdash;I won't&mdash;I won't, if I can help it&mdash;I'll look &s;o&mdash;ju&s;t &s;o, if I can&mdash;as &s;erious as a judge&mdash;will that do?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Looking &s;erious.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; that will do.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Rapping again.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(Going.)</HI> Ha, ha, ha, ha&mdash;I can't help laughing a little though&mdash;but not before her&mdash;I'll be as &s;erious as a judge before her. <HI>(A&s;ide)</HI> Egad I am afraid&mdash;I am afraid I &s;hall laugh.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit, &s;tifling a laugh.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now where &s;hall I run to have a peep at her?&mdash;in here.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit Flora.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> JEROME, <HI>bowing before the</HI> MARQUIS, <HI>with his face on one &s;ide, as if he was afraid to look at him for fear he &s;hould laugh.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let Don Antonio know I have letters for him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, your Honour&mdash;Lord&s;hip. <HI>(Lifting up his eyes, looking at him with &s;ide glances, and with difficulty &s;tifling a laugh.)</HI> Your Honour, your Lord|&s;hip&mdash;Let Don Antonio &mdash;know&mdash;you&mdash;have&mdash;let|tters&mdash;for&mdash;him. [<HI>Suppre&s;&s;ing a laugh.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; is not that plain?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes. <HI>(Still &s;uppre&s;&s;ing a laugh.)</HI> And he'll be very glad to wait upon your Honour.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Laughs right out and exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;trange fellow is this&mdash;How my heart beats!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><PB N="14" REF="020425_0015_0FC7417FDF1611A0">FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(From a door.)</HI> Oh that &s;he would but turn this way, that I might &s;ee her face&mdash;Oh the im|pudent &s;lut.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> JEROME, <HI>with a grin on his face.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Noble Lord, Don Antonio will be here immidiately. <HI>(Then laughs and &s;tares at him from head to foot.)</HI> Here he is.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ANTONIO.</STAGE>
<STAGE>(The Marquis bows very re&s;pectfully, whil&s;t Jerome is laughing and making faces behind.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Letters, my Lord, from your brother at Madrid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Signior.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Taking the letters.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(A&s;ide'while Antonio reads.)</HI> Heavens, whence this palpitation? If &s;uch are the feelings of my bo&s;om on knowing my&s;elf in the &s;ame hou&s;e with her, what mu&s;t be my agitation on a nearer approach!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>My letters inform me it is the Marquis who does me the honour of this vi&s;it&mdash;My Lord, your Lordship&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's the matter with you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I was only&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only what? Leave the room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(A&s;ide.)</HI> Well, I thought the old Don would have found out a woman in any di&s;gui&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, you may command my &s;er|vices and friend&s;hip, but I fear you will not rate them &s;o highly as I could wi&s;h, as you mu&s;t be debarred the acquaintance and &s;ociety of my niece&mdash;You are no &s;tranger to the vow &s;he has taken?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am not&mdash;and yet I flatter my&s;elf the manner in which I am &s;poken of in the&s;e letters&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be certain, Sir, my niece &s;hall receive them, urged with all my authority for an interview. Will your Lord&s;hip take a turn in the garden while I deliver them and enforce their contents?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will&mdash;and &s;hould you prove &s;ucce&s;s|ful, Don Antonio, I &s;hall ever retain the deepe&s;t &s;en&s;e of the obligation.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit Marquis.</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="15" REF="020425_0016_0FC74183D209E798"><HI>Enter the</HI> COUNTESS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Niece, I was this moment coming to you, to bring the&s;e letters from your uncle at Madrid, which you will find recommend, in the &s;tronge&s;t man|ner, to your acquaintance, no other than the young Marquis our neighbour&mdash;as fine a youth as ever I &s;aw.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha&mdash;is he arrived?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now in the hou&s;e&mdash;What is the matter?&mdash;Did you hear of his intended vi&s;it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;Ha, ha. ha&mdash;how does he look?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Delightfully&mdash;I don't think I ever &s;aw a hand&s;omer man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Man!</HI>&mdash;Ha, ha, ha; I dare &s;ay he looks a little awkward?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Awkward! No; he is as elegant in his deportment, and as fine, as fini&s;hed a young fellow as ever I &s;aw.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(After looking over the letter.)</HI> Cer|tainly I &s;hall comply with my uncle's reque&s;t&mdash;Let his Lord&s;hip be admitted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Niece, I always knew you could not keep your vow&mdash;I always knew the very fir&s;t man that came in your way&mdash;cra&s;h it would go direcly; but let me per&s;uade you to break it by degrees, and not let the world &s;ay you made no &s;truggle fir&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Struggle! Now, my dear Uncle, with all your deep di&s;cernment, particularly in regard to our &s;ex, to &s;ee you at la&s;t impo&s;ed upon delights me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;ed upon!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; for this &s;elf-&s;ame Marquis is a woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>A woman!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; this "fine, elegant creature."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>That is, then, the very rea&s;on why I thought her &s;o&mdash;"a fine creature,"&mdash;now that is intui|tion, in&s;tinct, love without knowing it&mdash;But, my dear niece, are you &s;ure you are right? Are you &s;ure you don't deceive me? Don't di&s;appoint me&mdash;I can't bear a di&s;appointment in a matter like this&mdash;I am va&s;tly plea&s;ed, and a di&s;appointment might be fatal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><PB N="16" REF="020425_0017_0FC7418CF0D16FC0">COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I a&s;&s;ure you again a woman&mdash;&s;i&s;ter to the Marquis&mdash;and has undertaken this &s;cheme purely to make love to me, and turn me into ridicule.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now I think of it again, &s;he <HI>was</HI> devili&s;h aukward&mdash;and I believe wore her &s;word on the wrong &s;ide.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is &s;he her&s;elf, depend upon it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure it is&mdash;and I'll be hang'd if it did not &s;trike me to be a woman the moment I laid my eyes on her&mdash;for &s;he came up to me &s;lipping and &s;liding, and to&s;&s;ing her head, ju&s;t as the fine ladies do. <HI>(Mimicks.)</HI> Well&mdash;but what do you intend to do? I know what I intend to do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall carry on the &s;cheme, and pre|tend to be deceived, till I turn the joke <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> de&s;igns for me on her&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; and I intend to have <HI>my</HI> joke too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>But you mu&s;t keep the &s;ecret.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't &s;ay a word.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Take his Lord&s;hip into the &s;aloon, and I'll wait upon him immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, my dear&mdash;and you need not be in a hurry&mdash;Egad, I like the joke of all things.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> JEROME <HI>and</HI> FLORA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear, my Lady, have you &s;een her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not yet.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I declare &s;he locks as like a man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall certainly laugh in her face.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh no, don't laugh&mdash;Never give your mind to laughing&mdash;I did not even &s;mile, but kept my countenance as &s;teady&mdash;ju&s;t thus&mdash;Did not I Flora? Oh&mdash;'tis &s;uch a weakne&s;s to laugh&mdash;Look ju&s;t &s;o&mdash;as I do now.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t away to the trial, however&mdash;come with me to the door. Flora.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>And be &s;ure you don't laugh&mdash;Think on me, and keep your countenance&mdash;if you can.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exit Counte&s;s and Flora on one &s;ide, and Jerome on the other.)</STAGE>
<P>END OF THE FIRST ACT.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="17" REF="020425_0018_0FC7418DE8F5EA88">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>The Hall in the Ca&s;tle.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> FLORA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<P>DEAR me, what a pretty footman &s;he has brought with her!&mdash;he made me &s;uch a fine bow as I pa&s;t, and looked &s;o grand&mdash;here he is.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CARLOS <HI>and bows&mdash;&s;he courte&s;ies.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Lord, I hope this is not a woman too! but I dare &s;ay it is&mdash;Lord what a pity! but I'll talk to him, and I &s;hall &s;oon be able to find out&mdash;and if he does not fall in love with me, I'll conclude it can't be a man.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>A very pretty girl. <HI>(A&s;ide.)</HI> Your hum|ble &s;ervant, my dear angel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Too conceited for a man.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>May I venture, on &s;o &s;light an acquain|tance to prote&s;t to you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;he prote&s;ts&mdash;'tis a man.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Permit me to a&s;&s;ure you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>What thus takes up your attention?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>A doubt I have.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you entertain any doubts of me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, indeed I do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>What are they?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have been trying to put this bunch of ribbons into a right form for my Lady's hair, and I hardly know how.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me try.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[She gives the ribbons.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now &s;hall I &s;ee, by the dexterity, whe|ther it is a woman or not.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>There&mdash;I'll be hang'd if I have not done it to a nicety.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Returns the ribbons.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis a woman, p&s;haw.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide and &s;ighing.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now I mu&s;t beg a ki&s;s for my pains.</P>
</SP>
<P>[<HI>Ki&s;&s;es her.</HI></P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;it mu&s;t be a man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>My charming&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>For Heaven's &s;ake go about your bu&s;ine&s;s, for here comes a fello-&s;ervant of mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><PB N="18" REF="020425_0019_0FC7418F42E90E60">CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am going <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> come there pre&s;ently?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;perhaps I may&mdash;only be gone now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>But you'll come!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;I think I will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CARLOS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall wait for you.</P>
</SP>
<P><HI>Enter</HI> URSULA.</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>URSULA.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, Mrs. Flora, I give you joy of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> new &s;weetheart&mdash;For &s;hame, for &s;hame, I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> pa&s;&s;ed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord ble&s;s you&mdash;it is only a woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>URSULA.</SPEAKER>
<P>A woman!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, in men's clothes, like the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> and &s;o there could be no harm you <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>URSULA.</SPEAKER>
<P>I did not know the &s;ervant was a wo|man too!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I am not &s;ure of it&mdash;but i thought &s;o when I let him ki&s;s me, and I thought &s;o when I promi&s;ed to meet him in the grove&mdash;and I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> go&mdash;for I dare &s;ay 'tis only a woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>URSULA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, now I think of it again, I am &s;ure it is not a man&mdash;Do you &s;uppose a Lady in di&s;|gui&s;e would take a man-&s;ervant to attend her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very true; and I wi&s;h, Ur&s;ula, you would go in&s;tend of me in the grove for I am &s;o bu&s;y ju&s;t at this time&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>URSULA.</SPEAKER>
<P>And yet old Jerome &s;ays, and I never knew Jerome mi&s;taken in my life, he &s;ays it is a man; however, I am not afraid of him if it is, and I <HI>will</HI> go in&s;tead of you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLORA.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Ur&s;ula&mdash;I will go after all&mdash;for it <HI>&s;hould</HI> prove a man, and he &s;hould behave rude to you, oh! my dear Ur&s;ula, I &s;hould never be happy, that I did not take it all upon my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt &s;eparately.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>A Parlour in the Ca&s;tle.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>The</HI> COUNTESS, <HI>the</HI> MARQUIS, <HI>and</HI> DON AN|TONIO <HI>di&s;covered &s;itting.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO,</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o, my Lord, you once thought of the army&mdash;Do you think you &s;hould &s;tand your ground in a battle?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Laughing to him&s;elf.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><PB N="19" REF="020425_0020_0FC74190B6C2FB60">MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Surpri&s;ed.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(A&s;ide.)</HI> Damn me but &s;he has a good leg.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lord&s;hip &s;eems formed for the &s;ervice of a &s;ofter Deity; an occupation le&s;s perilous than that of war.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, that you do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pardon me, Madam, the Deity you allude to, I fear may be yet more fatal, unle&s;s you will kindly fight on my &s;ide.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha; I can't help laughing to think what a pretty &s;oldier you would make&mdash;You look va&s;tly like a &s;oldier to be &s;ure.&mdash;Ha, ha, ha.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why not, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Angrily.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, no offence&mdash;Damn me if I &s;hould not like to command a whole regiment of you&mdash;and I would go upon &s;ome new atchievements&mdash;For in&s;tance, &s;ay the enemy were Hottentots, I would un|dertake to poi&s;on them all by the &s;cent of perfumes from my army&mdash;or in ca&s;e of a repul&s;e, would en|gage at any time to rai&s;e a mi&s;t, and e&s;cape pur&s;uit, only by commanding every man to &s;hake his head, and di&s;charge the powder.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word, Sir, you are very plea&s;ant.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Forcing a &s;mile.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am very glad your Lord&s;hip thinks &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SERVANT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERVANT.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(To Antonio.)</HI> Sir, you are wanted by a gentleman in the parlour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw, I'm bu&s;y&mdash;Who is it? <HI>(Servant whi&s;pers.)</HI> Well then I mu&s;t come. <HI>(Exit Servant.)</HI> My Lord, I take my leave for a minute, but I &s;hall &s;oon be back, <HI>(A&s;ide)</HI> How like a man &s;he looks&mdash;Impudent hu&s;&s;ey.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your uncle's behaviour, Madam, has &s;omething in it rather extraordinary&mdash;I hope I have not in any means offended him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can conceal my knowledge of her no longer, <HI>(A&s;ide.)</HI> Oh no, my dear, not at all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear! <HI>(A&s;ide.)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I declare I like you &s;o well&mdash;&s;o much
<PB N="20" REF="020425_0021_0FC74198F9268610">
better than I expected&mdash;I can no longer treat you with cold re&s;erve&mdash;Come &s;it down.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[They &s;it.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>How kind is this!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Drawing his chair near to her.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(Looking at him from head to feet.)</HI> Ha, ha, ha, ha, ha. I prote&s;t I can't help laughing&mdash;Ha, ha, ha, ha, ha.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha, ha, ha, ha&mdash;I prote&s;t no more can I&mdash;Sure fate directed me to this heavenly &s;pot, where ceremony has no &s;hare in politene&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>And did you &s;uppo&s;e I &s;hould u&s;e any ceremony with &s;uch a &s;weet, &s;weet fellow as you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad, I'll u&s;e no ceremony either. <HI>(A&s;ide.)</HI> Thus, on my knees, let me pour my thanks.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh you artful creature!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Stroking his cheek.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Art! I di&s;claim it&mdash;and &s;o do you&mdash;You are all pure nature.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I po&s;itively do think you one of the clevere&s;t of your whole &s;ex.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank you.&mdash;Thank you&mdash;my deare&s;t creature.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Ki&s;&s;ing her hand.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>So negligent&mdash;&s;o ea&s;y&mdash;not the lea&s;t awkward or embarra&s;&s;ed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad, I think you as little embarra&s;&s;ed to the full. <HI>(A&s;ide.)</HI> My dear Madam, your char|ming &s;ociety has in&s;pired me.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Salutes her.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now if you were really a <HI>man,</HI> what would you <HI>de&s;erve</HI> for that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(A&s;toni&s;hed.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay, if you were <HI>really</HI> a man, what would you de&s;erve for that freedom?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Really</HI> a man! Why?&mdash;What&mdash;Don't I look like a man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;that you do&mdash;and a &s;weet pretty man&mdash;Come, come, don't be frightened&mdash;&s;hake hands&mdash;I forgive you&mdash;forgive you all your impertinence&mdash;and, early the je&s;t as far as you will, I am re&s;olved not to be angry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am very much obliged to you&mdash;in|finitely obliged to you&mdash;I a&s;&s;ure you this favour&mdash;this
<PB N="21" REF="020425_0022_0FC7419BF5150CE0">
honour&mdash;I don't know what to &s;ay&mdash;She ab&s;olutely puts me out of countenance.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>What confu&s;ed? Come, re&s;ume your gaiety&mdash;Come, come&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, then</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Seizing her.</STAGE>
<P><HI>Enter</HI> DON ANTONIO.</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hah!&mdash;What! Struggling?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Uncle, I have been &s;o ill-u&s;ed by this Gentleman, that I mu&s;t beg you will re&s;ent his behaviour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly, my dear, if you <HI>have</HI> been u&s;ed ill.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mo&s;t &s;candalou&s;ly&mdash;Frighten her a little.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide to Antonio.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my honour, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds, Sir, my Niece is one of the mo&s;t re&s;erved, prudent young women&mdash;and who&s;oever offers an in&s;ult to her, it is my place, and con&s;i&s;tent but with my honour, to re&s;ent it.&mdash;How white &s;he looks.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I &s;hall not draw my &s;word before the Counte&s;s, and therefore I beg you will put up yours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o I will, my poor Lady&mdash;I &s;ee it has frightened you&mdash;Here, Niece, have you any hart&s;horn or drops at hand&mdash;the poor thing is terrified out of her life. Come, come, my poor little creature&mdash;Poor thing&mdash;Poor rogue.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(He goes up to &s;ooth him, and the Marquis gives him a blow.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don Antonio, this in&s;olence &s;hall re|ceive the correction it de&s;erves.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Draws.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>She is not in earne&s;t, &s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have received many a blow from a Lady, but never &s;uch a one as this!.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQ.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you dare to call me a Lady again, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Lady, oh no&mdash;you are a tyger, a fury.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQ.</SPEAKER>
<P>I never met with &s;uch u&s;age!&mdash;Damnation!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a profligate &s;he is! I did not think &s;uch a word could come out of a woman's mouth!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, Sir!&mdash;Dare you &s;ay that again, and I'll nail you to the wall.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><PB N="22" REF="020425_0023_0FC741A4EE2BD300">ANTO.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(Retreating.)</HI> Why, what is all this about? I won't fight&mdash;I only drew my &s;word to frighten you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>To frighten me!&mdash;Did you think I was to be frightened?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why not! you &s;ee I am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I &s;ee, and &s;corn you for it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Uncle, the tables are fairly turned upon you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Niece, and I'm much obliged to you, for your advice in the bu&s;ine&s;s&mdash;But you may depend upon it, I &s;hall take care how I attempt to frighten one of your &s;ex again.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Going.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come back, Sir; I in&s;i&s;t upon your coming back, and recalling what you have &s;aid&mdash;I in&s;i&s;t upon your begging my pardon for your imperti|nent in&s;inuation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>What in&s;inuation?&mdash;That I think you a female?&mdash;I am &s;ure there is no offence meant in that&mdash;for, when I &s;uppo&s;e you a woman, I &s;uppo&s;e you what I like better than any thing in the world; what I am never happy without; and what I even make my&s;elf poor, de&s;pi&s;ed, and ridiculous, in the daily pur&s;uit of.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>And pray, Sir, in what do I appear like a woman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>And pray, Sir, in what does any of our modern coxcombs appear like a man? and yet they don't &s;cruple to call them&s;elves men.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then you will not recall your &s;enti|ments and beg my pardon?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Beg your pardon?&mdash;No&mdash;Yes, yes&mdash;Put on your petticoates, and I'll fall at your feet as &s;oon as you plea&s;e.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll bear this no longer&mdash;Draw.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Marquis draws.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here Jerome, Jerome, come and defend me, where it would be a di&s;honour to defend my&s;elf</P>
</SP>
<P><HI>Enter</HI> JEROME.</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>See, Jerome, how my life is a&s;&s;ailed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, your Honour, I always told you the women would be the death of you at la&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><PB N="23" REF="020425_0024_0FC741A5E90403E8">MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>You too, ra&s;cal!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I declare with her &s;word in her hand, &s;he is as fine a creature as ever I &s;aw!&mdash;Oh you audacious minx!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Scoundrel&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sure, your Honour, &s;he mu&s;t be the Maid of Orleans.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am no maid, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;orry for your misfortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don Antonio, this treatment I &s;uppo&s;e you inflict as a ju&s;t recompence for my pre&s;umption in daring to hope for an alliance in your family, &s;pite of the prejudice which I knew the Counte&s;s had conceiv|ed. I cannot deny the ju&s;tice of the accu&s;ation&mdash;I came into her hou&s;e with the vain hope&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>By no means <HI>vain</HI>&mdash;I am ready to comply, be your hopes what they will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can I believe what you &s;ay real?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly&mdash;Were you going to &s;ay you hoped to marry me? If you were, call the Prie&s;t, and we'll be married immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, if that is what your Lord&s;hip wants, the Prie&s;t &s;hall tack you together in five minutes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>This &s;udden con&s;ent &s;taggers me&mdash;I was not prepared for it&mdash;one likes a little preparation before marriage as well as before death.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! you are ca&s;t down&mdash;alarmed&mdash;want to recant&mdash;but I won't let you&mdash;You <HI>&s;hall</HI> marry me&mdash;I in&s;i&s;t upon it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! directly?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, directly&mdash;I am in a hurry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I believe this is mere trifling&mdash;Swear you will marry me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do &s;wear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are witne&s;s to the oath.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO <HI>and</HI> JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>We are witne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<P><HI>Enter</HI> SERVANT <HI>with</HI> DONNA ISABELLA <HI>vailed.</HI></P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERVANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Lady, Madam, who &s;ays &s;he is &s;i&s;ter to the Marquis.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has the Marquis more &s;i&s;ters than one?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><PB N="24" REF="020425_0025_0FC741A751D0AF28">MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>No.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then this, I &s;uppo&s;e, is your brother?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEROME.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, in women's clothes&mdash;O dear, another fine &s;ight!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Heavens! if it is a man take him out of the room or I &s;hall faint.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>Si&s;ter I&s;abella, when I &s;hall relate to you the &s;trange reception I have met with in this hou&s;e, you will be amazed&mdash;but I think you will &s;incerely re|joice at the final event of my vi&s;it, when I tell you it is a &s;olemn promi&s;e from this Lady to become my wife.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I give you joy mo&s;t unfeignedly.</P>
</SP>
<P>[<HI>Pulls off her veil.</HI></P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is a <HI>woman.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, that it is&mdash;Madam, let me bid you welcome to the ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Goes and &s;alutes her.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(To the Marquis.)</HI> Why, what are you <HI>(After trembling as if much terrified)</HI> an't <HI>you</HI> a woman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Counte&s;s, I knew you never would have con&s;ented to have &s;een the Marquis, had he been intro|duced into the hou&s;e as a man, therefore I formed this &s;tratagem, unknown to him, thus to bring you together.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(To the Counte&s;s.)</HI> Do not droop, my deare&s;t wife.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>And are you really the Marquis? What a &s;trange blunder have I made!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MARQUIS.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am the Marquis&mdash;and it &s;hall be my future care to bani&s;h for ever from your memory, the recollection of that marriage which has been the &s;ource of &s;o much woe to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>Donna I&s;abella, we are all infinitely <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> for this &s;tratagem, by which you have <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> the Counte&s;s, innocently to break a vow, which &s;he could not have kept without drawing upon her&s;elf both ridicule and melancholy&mdash;My dear Niece, depend upon it, there is but <HI>one</HI> vow a woman is au|thori<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> to take.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>COUNTESS.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what vow is that <HI>one,</HI> Uncle?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ANTONIO.</SPEAKER>
<P>And vow to LOVE, HONOUR, and OBEY.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt omnes.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<TRAILER>THE END.</TRAILER>
